  "text": "Mice were humanely killed, and whole eyes from transgenic and nontransgenic mice were enucleated and fixed for 2 hours in 0.1 M phosphate buffer (pH 7.4) containing 4% formaldehyde, after which the lens was removed and the remaining tissue was placed in phosphate-buffered paraformaldehyde for an additional 12 hours of fixation at 4°C. Eyes were embedded, sectioned, and stained with appropriate primary and commercially available, fluorescence-conjugated (FITC and Cy3) secondary antibodies (see figure legends), as described. [CITATION_1] The 3B6 anti-Rds antibody (kindly provided by Robert Molday) was used at a 1:5 dilution with phosphate-buffered saline (PBS) containing 0.2% Triton X-100. Anti-human blue opsin antibody (a generous gift from Jeremy Nathans, Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, MD) was used at a 1:3000 dilution. The density of the blue cones was assessed across a retinal expanse 100-m in length at a distance 300 m from the edge of the optic nerve head in the inferior hemisphere, corresponding to the retinal region of highest blue cone content.",
